 benefit these (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) by deciding/figuring out the extent to 
 which it is possible to raise working well by improving the neglected source, (in other words), (wasting very little while working or producing something), with the 
 existing useful thing/valuable supply base and the available technology. 
 Hence, by doing so, they could also help decide 
 whether to improve (wasting very little while working or producing something) first or develop a new 
 technology in the short run. 
 Having to do with the long-lasting view in literature that 
 farmers practising traditional farming are 'poor 
 but (producing a lot with very little waste)', and the resulting focus on increased investments in creating new and more 
 productive ways of doing things, a few studies that (examined closely) the relationship between farm size and output 
 in Indian farming have been managed and did/done since the 
 late 1950s. (related to a large area) differences/different versions, together with 
 
