 taken into account since the 1960s. These include the 
 works of Saini (1969), Sahota (1968), Hopper (1965). 
 These studies were managed and did/done to test, recommend and plan appropriate productive ways of doing things that lead to improved useful thing/valuable supply-use (wasting very little while working or producing something). 
 However, as they represented the production process 
 of the sample farms on an input-output space (production function) with a given technology, they were 
 not able to separate causes of (wasting very little while working or producing something) due the 
 (related to the body function of living things) nature of farming-based production from the 
 farm-clearly stated/particular differences in the use of the available 
 technology. 
 Later, (even though there is the existence of) the idea-based (problems, delays, etc.) and (related to careful studying or deep thinking) differences, (wasting very little while working or producing something) measurements have 
 been attempted in Indian farming since the 1970s 
 (see for example, Huang and Bagi (1984), Kalirajan 
 (1981), Junankar (1980), Sidhu (1974), and Lau and 
 Yotopoulos (1971); in fact, the last thing just mentioned two measured 
 relative technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) using shadow profit 
 function). With particular reference to rice farming, 
 the studies by Shanmugam and Palanisami (1993) in 
 Tamil Nadu, Datt and Joshi (1992) in Uttar Pradesh, 
 and Jayaram et al. (1987) in Karnataka are among 
 the well-known/obvious works. These studies, although framed 
 on pre-decided or (related to the study of how likely or unlikely things are to happen) guesses of the 
 edge of something/unexplored area production function, reported a mean technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) of 75%, 66% and 74% among paddy 
 farms in the (pertaining to each person or thing) states. 
 On the other hand, although we watch/notice wider 
 applications of (wasting very little while working or producing something) measures in paddy farms 
 of India, only very few of these studies have (examined closely) the same across size groups and agro-(related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) areas (zones) (at the same time). Besides, there is 
 no agreement among the available studies on the 
 old debate of (wasting very little while working or producing something) differences in the smallvs. large-sized farms. The earlier idea was that, 
 under the usual labour intensive technology, 
 output per hectare on large farms was lower mainly 
 because of higher cost of hired labour. Anyway, 
 with the progressive introduction of technology, new 
 production possibilities have been opened for large 
 farms (Singh, 1992). Therefore, with their better 
 capital position, as well as institutional, extension 
 and credit advantages, large farmers can 
 substitute manpower by labour-saving devices; this way, 
 they are (producing more with less waste) than small farms. Available 
 (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) hints that different factors cause differ- 
 
 ences in (wasting very little while working or producing something) even among farms of almost the same  size 
 and other factors of production. The debate will 
 further be heated when (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) ((related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth)) 
 issues are incorporated. This is an important issue of 
 the present time, because (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) issues are the 
 core elements of (able to last/helping the planet) development. The present study, therefore, is an attempt partly aimed at 
 (asking lots of questions about/trying to find the truth about) technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) in paddy farms 
 across (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) zones and farm size groups and 
 their interactions in the southern Indian state of 
 Tamil Nadu. 
 
 2. The study area and data 
 The state of Tamil Nadu is one of the major 
 rice-growing areas of India that is located in the 
 southeastern extremity of the Indian peninsula. With 
 basically a (related to areas near the Equator/hot and humid) climate of 18Â°C-43Â°C (minimum 
 and maximum daily temperatures), the state receives 
 an average of 925 mm once-a-year rainfall distributed 
 over four major seasons: the Southwest bad rainstorm 
 (Jun.-Dec.), Northeast bad rainstorm (Oct.-Dec.), Winter (Jan.-Feb.) and Summer (Mar.-May). A mostly red soil, lateral black and (from floodwaters) soils 
 good for (producing crops/helping something grow) of cereals and fibre crops 
 win in the state. 
 The state is divided into seven clear/separate agroclimatic zones; that is,, the Western zone (Zone-1 in this 
 study), Southern zone (Zone-11), Northeastern zone 
 (Zone-ill) and the Cauvery Delta area (Zone-IV). 
 The remaining three zones include the Northwestern 
 (dry belt) zone, the high-rainfall coastal areas and the 
 hilly zone, which completely account for (compared to other things) 
 less than 15% of the total area under rice in the state. 
 Due to their special features and the (almost nothing/very little) area 
 under rice, the last three zones were not thought about/believed 
 in this study. 
 Data having to do with crop (producing crops/helping something grow) in all agroclimatic zones of the state, collected from 60 groups 
 taken on a (fair in amount, related to something else/properly sized compared to something else) random sampling basis, are 
 available for each year in the complete big plan/layout/dishonest plan 
 for guessing the cost of (producing crops/helping something grow) for principal 
 crops (CCPC) in the Department of Farming-based 
 Money flow, Tamil Nadu Farming-based University. 
 Data for the present study refer to 129 high-cooperating with/producing/giving up 
 variety rice (IR-20) growers distributed over the 
 four zones during the major production season of 
 
 B. Tadesse, S. Krishnamoorthy j Farming-based Money flow 16 (1997) 185-192 
 
 October-December (Northeast bad rainstorm) for the year 
 1992/1993. Although rice is grown in two seasons, 
 a single production season was selected in order to 
 (make small) the effect of (change depending on the season) on input 
 use and the yield. HYV rice (IR-20) was selected 
 due to its wider (producing crops/helping something grow) in the state during the 
 particular season. Further, the analysis was limited to 
 the first four zones in order to maintain evenness, by leaving out/keeping out zones with special features and 
 which are less good for rice (producing crops/helping something grow). 
 
